Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

The FCO advise against all but essential travel to the whole country.

Coronavirus: stay up to date
See information on measures introduced in St Kitts and Nevis in response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic. Find out how to return to the UK from St Kitts and Nevis.
See coronavirus travel advice for guidance on international travel.
Sign up for email alerts for St Kitts and Nevis travel advice.
Currently the borders of St Kitts and Nevis are closed to all arriving passengers. Access is not available either through the sea port or the airport either to nationals, residents or non-nationals.
From Saturday 4 April 1900 a full 24 hour curfew is in force until Wednesday 8 April 0600 (full 24 hour lockdown on Sunday, Monday and Tuesday ending Wednesday at 0600). On Wednesday 8 April and Thursday 9 April, people can leave their homes to purchase food and medicines only between 0600 and 1900. A curfew remains in place Wednesday from 1900 to 0600 Thursday
Only essential services – security, utilities, emergency and media – personnel will be allowed outside their homes. See Return to the UK.
Most visits to St Kitts and Nevis are trouble-free but there have been incidents of crime including murder, armed robbery and sexual assault. See Crime
Consular support may be limited in St Kitts and Nevis as there is no British High Commission office.  However, the British High Commission in Bridgetown, Barbados can provide consular support.
The hurricane season normally runs from June to November. You should monitor local and international weather updates from the US National Hurricane Centre and follow the advice of local authorities, including any evacuation orders. See Natural disasters
UK health authorities have classified St Kitts and Nevis as having a risk of Zika virus transmission. For information and advice about the risks associated with Zika virus, visit the National Travel Health Network and Centre website.
Although there’s no recent history of terrorism in St Kitts and Nevis, attacks can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
